result.execSummary:
The defendant Magia E. Horaitis was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess/Illegally Obtained Prescription [Modifiers: Repeater], an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 450.11(7)(h).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Must seek and maintain full-time employment which is satisfactory to your probation agent.  Defendant  must not leave or change employment without prior approval of your probation agent.

Not to possess or consume any controlled substances.   Not to possess any drug paraphernalia.  Not to possess any prescription medications of any kind unless those have been prescribed to the defendant by a physician, and in that case, the defendant shall take such medications only as prescribed.  Defendant shall not alter the form of any prescription prior to, or in conjunction with, ingestion.

Must use only 1 pharmacy for prescriptions and must identify that pharmacy to your probation agent.  May use another pharmacy only if your agent gives you permission to so.  Must sign a release for your agent to verify compliance.

The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by a risk and needs assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.

Must submit a DNA sample and pay the surcharge.

If probation is revoked and a prison term is not ordered, or if probation is discharged or terminated, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of any restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.  If the defendant is placed on probation or released to extended supervision, IT IS ORDERED that the defendant pay supervision fees as determined by the Department of Corrections.

Court finds the defendant understands the proceedings has entered her plea F,V,K,I and accepts the plea.  State recommends sentence withheld and probation with conditions.  Attorney Terrien states it a joint recommendation.  City citations are to be dismissed by authorization from the City attorney to DA.  Court orders all citations dismissed and read-in.  Defendant excercises her right to allocution.
